                                <p>
                                    Dear delegates,
                                </p>
                                <p>My name is Rishi Raj Deva, and I am pleased to welcome you the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC). For this year’s committee, I’d strongly advise delegates to familiarise themselves with nature and scope of this committee, and what it entails. I expect arguments and speeches to be logical and nuanced. Don’t bring a big stack of research material and gun me with facts which ultimately lead to nothing, the purpose is to test your diplomacy skills, not your research skills, even though they do still count, obviously.</p>
                                <p>Both the agendas I have chosen encompass a wide range of issues pertaining to illicit drug use and the perpetuation of terrorism and organised crime. Narco-terrorism has long since served as a means of funding for terrorist organisations and the intimidation and control of governments, the most famous example being Pablo Escobar who led the Medellin drug cartel and terrorised the Colombian government during his time as a drug lord, thus forcing them to re-evaluate its extradition treaty. Similarly Cyber Espionage is one of the most recent yet most prominent issues in the modern world of cyberspace and has only been facilitated due to increased cyber dependency. In 2009, a cyber-espionage network called ‘Ghost-Net’ accessed confidential information belonging to both governmental and private organisations in over 100 countries around the world. Cyber conflicts can be seen as a mirror of their real-world counterparts, but also increasingly as completely independent disputes, clashes, attacks and perhaps acts of war in an emerging arena.</p>
                                <p>As for myself, I have been in the MUN circuit for about 3 years now. I’ve attended both national and international MUNs., I have taken part in committees ranging from 15 to 350 people and everything in between, including GA’s, SC’s and specialised committees. I am an avid debater, reader and while most of my time is spent in dealing with the relentlessness of the IB, what I can salvage is spent mostly at the gym or at the squash courts.</p>
                                <p>All that remains for me to say is that gear up, prepare and make the best of your time at Chandbagh. For those new to MUN, I’d strongly recommend using this experience as a platform for future MUNs and the rest, fully engage in debate and be an active part of committee. Remember, delegates that while research and eloquence do play an important role, the true test of your skill lies in diplomacy and that is exactly what I hope DSMUN, this year, can bring out of you.</p>
                                <div class="signing-off">
