                        <div id="agenda-intro">
                          <h2>Introduction to Agenda</h2>
                          <div class="divide20"></div>
                          <h3>Agenda 1: Narco-Terrorism</h3>
                          <p>Narco-terrorism, according to the US Drug Enforcement Agency, refers to the “participation of groups or associated individuals in taxing, providing security for, otherwise aiding or abetting drug trafficking endeavors in an effort to further, or fund, terrorist activities” (Holmberg, 2009). In this context, a clear line needs to be drawn between the two aspects of the issue: Drugs and Terrorism. Terrorist groups such as the Colombian FARC and the Taliban in Afghanistan, among Others, are considered to use narcotic and illicit drugs trafficking as a way to finance their actions. This kind of narco-terrorism suggests that trafficking enables these groups to have the funds to achieve their separate agendas. In reality, trafficking and armed violence by members of drug cartels and narco-terrorist groups can become a separate activity on its own, to which politics is secondary. The number of drug related deaths today is at an all-time high, taking millions of lives annually. Moreover, these numbers are expected to grow in coming years due to exponential increases in drug addiction, only driven by the influence of narco-terrorism.</p>
                          <h3>Agenda 2: Cyber Espionage amongst Non-State Actors</h3>
                          <p>The creation of Cyberspace also led to the creation of threats to cyber security. The often cited “cyber-attacks” on targets in Estonia in the spring of 2007 is a clear example of where volunteers actively took part in an open cyber conflict, acting as a sort of cyber militia, by rallying to overload various cyberspace resources, such as Estonian government and commercial web services. Another famous and much heard of is example is Anonymous, a collective of so-called “hacktivists”, who have been claiming responsibility for several widely publicised web defacements, information leaks, denial-of-service attacks, and other cyber actions sometimes related to national security or military affaires. All countries may be affected by this. Large countries can be tempted and may get into conflicts because they have the power and ability to conduct cyber espionage on another country. Smaller countries may be affected because they are a much easier target. They can be weaker and tend to be coerced by larger and stronger countries. Also, clear limitations must be set in order to distinguish between which acts can or cannot be considered as cyber-crime. The moral aspect of the issue is also one which needs to be discussed. Keeping this in mind, this issue needs to see a fairly unanimous resolution due to it’s potential to affect several countries worldwide.</p>
                        </div>
